The sailors patrol the covered naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings wave a navy blue flag.
Naval bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are pampered with the motto: “The sea is ours by right.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Around the landlocked territory of Bolivia, the memory of a coast lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still very vivid, as is the desire to sail again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps the deepest in decades, as Bolivia awaits the resolution that the International Court of Justice will issue on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity, and, needless to say, it looks forward to the result with a positive stance,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will look at the IJT’s resolution on large screens across the country, hoping that the Hague Court will rule in favor of Bolivia’s claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile is obliged to negotiate the granting of a sovereign exit to the sea for Bolivia.
