John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a track record of academic excellence that has continued into 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, for the career they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we observe that modern languages remain a very popular and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you will get to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot depend only on English if we want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that the languages lead the ranking tables with the highest ratings in independent schools.
Sixty-eight percent of students who studied foreign languages scored higher.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools reflected that 72% of students obtained a higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as a subject of choice, are kept in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in curricula from independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK’s Employment and Competence Commission revealed that of the reasons employers gave for the cost of filling vacancies, 17% was attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
As there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competition like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find important jobs.
In Scotland there is diversity among schools in terms of the languages taught.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be more important for the UK in the future, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interest of your child, you can always choose from a number of languages in independent schools, which have teaching staff specializing in this area.
Independent Scottish schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the necessary skills to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
In the global business environment of today, there is no denying that languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered “international communicative competences”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
