North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were intensifying its distrust of the United States and that, under such circumstances, the country would not unilaterally eliminate its nuclear weapons in any way.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" during the previous year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear testing center and pledging not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we are not observing any response in line with the U.S.,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and, under these circumstances, we will not initiate disarmament unilaterally in any way.”
While Ri resumed North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization approach for which North Korea would be rewarded as it took action gradually, his statements seemed significant because he did not reject unilateral full denuclearization, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a serving U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea has tried to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted the call to relax the harsh international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that denuclearization must occur first and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, in addition to opposing the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions will make us kneel is a chimera of people who don’t know anything about us.
