Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page in the "Sunday Morning" Almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and counting... the day the physicist of the future, Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually resulted in the device known as the Geiger counter.
The Geiger counter, which has been a mainstay of science ever since, also became a stack of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado," starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, a seemingly failed cowboy physicist:
Man: "What the hell is this?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, which is used to find radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you can hear the effects of atoms emanating from radioactivity on minerals."
Evans: "I'm sure it's exploding now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days after his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name is still alive.
New Cancer Vaccine May Teach the Immune System to ‘See’ Malignant Cells
New Cancer Vaccine May Teach the Immune System to ‘See’ and Kill Malignant Cells
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize these malignant cells as part of the treatment
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory.
You can "see" a protein common to many cancers and then re-inject them
A trial vaccine is showing promising results in patients with various types of cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient, altering them in the laboratory to be able to "see" a protein present in many types of cancer (HER2), and subsequently re-injecting them.
According to Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, “The results we obtained suggest that we have a promising vaccine.”
The HER2 protein "favors the growth of several types of cancer", including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer, said Professor Berzofsky.
A similar approach to extracting immune cells from patients and “teaching” these cells how to treat cancer cells has worked in treating a type of leukemia.
