What is the Global Citizen Festival? Have you done anything to reduce poverty?
New York will host this Saturday the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event, which presents an absolutely impressive program of stars, who carry out an equally impressive mission: to eradicate poverty in the world.
For the seventh time this year, the Global Citizen Festival will see tens of thousands of people gather in the Great Lawn area of Central Park not only to enjoy performances such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness of the event’s global goal of ending extreme poverty in the world by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which began in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people who help actively combat it.
To receive a free ticket to the event (unless someone wants to pay for a VIP ticket), attendees had to do a number of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, emailing a world leader, making a phone call or any other activity to raise awareness about the goal of ending poverty.
What achievements has Global Citizen achieved now that it has 12 years to reach its goal?
The idea of rewarding people with a free concert is a good way to persuade them to demand a call to action or just one more case of what we call “clictivism” (people who think it makes a difference by signing an online petition or sending a tweet?
Since 2011, Global Citizen claims to have recorded more than 19 million “actions” from its supporters, which have helped achieve several goals.
These actions have helped spur world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, which will have impacted the lives of more than 2.2 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group mentioned 390 commitments and announcements derived from its shares, of which at least USD 10 billion has already been disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that so far protected funds have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition Foundation, a UK-based association of investors and filmmakers, which pledges to “help children grow as much as possible” and pledges to send $35 million to Rwanda to help combat malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“Thanks to the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and members of Global Citizens, like you, we can turn the social injustice of malnutrition into a footnote in history,” The Power of Nutrition Ambassador Tracey Ullman told the crowd during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also explained that after more than 5,000 actions calling for the UK to improve the nutrition of mothers and children, the government announced funding for a project, The Power of Nutrition, which will reach 5 million women and children with nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the Q&As on his website asking "what makes you think we can end extreme poverty?",
Global Citizen responded: "It will be a long and hard road. Sometimes we will fall and fail.
But like the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements of the past, we will triumph, because together we are stronger.”
