How the U.S.-China trade war could benefit Beijing
The initial salves of the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and while the war does not seem to be ending soon, a distancing of countries may prove beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts said.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued his first warning earlier this year when he imposed taxes on China’s major exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week, with new tariffs affecting products worth USD 200 billion. These tariffs involve a taxation on half of all goods arriving in the US from China.
Beijing has repeatedly counter-attacked in the same way and recently raised tariffs from five percent to ten percent on $60 billion worth of American goods.
China has pledged to replicate the U.S. and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to be pulled back anytime soon.
Getting Washington to back down means giving in to some demands, but publicly bowing down to the US would be too shameful for Xi Jinping, the President of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of the trade war with the US could benefit China in the long run by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing could create the conditions that start a fall in any of these countries is far more dangerous than witnesses had anticipated,” said Abigail Grace, Asia-centered research associate at the Center for New American Security, an expert committee.
Syria 'prepared' for return of refugees, foreign minister says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country, devastated by a war of more than seven years.
Speaking at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country are improving.
“Currently, the situation on the street is more stable and safe, thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas that the terrorists shattered to restore normalcy.
All conditions are met for the voluntary return of refugees to the country who had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and maintenance.
The EU estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
There are also six million people living in the country and in need of humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime appreciates any help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from the countries that financed the insurgency.
