Red tide update: concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more scattered proliferation conditions are being reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier areas, suggesting a lower concentration.
Red tide proliferation extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Spots can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations on or off the coast in Pinellas County have been reported over the past week, low-to-high concentrations on or off the coast in Hillsborough County, low-to-low concentrations in Manatee County, medium-to-low concentrations in Charlotte County, low-to-low concentrations in or off the coast in Le Collier County, high-to-low concentrations in or off the coast.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeast Florida.
